<dl id="n14027c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14027c">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14027c"> 27(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> held up to / contumacy ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n14027c"><li>FW 115.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n14027c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n14027c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n14027c">MS BL 47473-45v</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:350 <a name="ed3y" href="../../ff/fdra/eda.htm#ed3y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed3.htm#n14027c">Draft: I.5&sect;1.3</a>+/4.3+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">So also did this singer <mark>hold up to contumacy</mark> the materialism and immorality of the Roman hierarchy, who &ldquo;filled their Guelphish coffers&rdquo; with German gold and silver, in order that their &ldquo;priests might eat capons and quaff wine,&rdquo; while Germans &ldquo;prayed and fasted for them.&rdquo; The farce of Absolution came equally under the sting of his lash, von der Vogelweide solemnly asserting that God alone had the power to forgive sins, and that a Pope who dared to assume this right, without first having convinced himself of the sinner&apos;s penitence, deserved to be stoned as soon as ever he consigned one man to hell. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 4-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
